items.abstract:
<jats:title>Abstract</jats:title>
            <jats:p>Given a finite relational language <jats:italic>L</jats:italic> is there an algorithm that, given two finite sets <jats:inline-graphic xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" mime-subtype="gif" xlink:href="S0022481200020284_inline1" xlink:type="simple" /> and <jats:inline-graphic xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" mime-subtype="gif" xlink:href="S0022481200020284_inline2" xlink:type="simple" /> of structures in the language, determines how many homogeneous <jats:italic>L</jats:italic> structures there are omitting every structure in <jats:inline-graphic xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" mime-subtype="gif" xlink:href="S0022481200020284_inline2" xlink:type="simple" /> and embedding every structure in <jats:inline-graphic xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" mime-subtype="gif" xlink:href="S0022481200020284_inline1" xlink:type="simple" />?</jats:p>
            <jats:p>For directed graphs this question reduces to: Is there an algorithm that, given a finite set of tournaments Γ, determines whether <jats:inline-graphic xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" mime-subtype="gif" xlink:href="S0022481200020284_inline3" xlink:type="simple" />
               <jats:sub>Γ</jats:sub>, the class of finite tournaments omitting every tournament in Γ. is well-quasi-order?</jats:p>
            <jats:p>First, we give a nonconstructive proof of the existence of an algorithm for the case in which Γ consists of one tournament. Then we determine explicitly the set of tournaments each of which does not have an antichain omitting it. Two antichains are exhibited and a summary is given of two structure theorems which allow the application of Kruskal's Tree Theorem. Detailed proofs of these structure theorems will be given elsewhere.</jats:p>
            <jats:p>The case in which Γ consists of two tournaments is also discussed.</jats:p>
title: Finitely constrained classes of homogeneous directed graphs
